title:
Approximate Feedback Nash Equilibria with Sparse Inter-Agent
  Dependencies

sections.text:
#### Abstract

Feedback Nash equilibrium strategies in multi-agent dynamic games require availability of all players' state information to compute control actions. However, in real-world scenarios, sensing and communication limitations between agents make full state feedback expensive or impractical, and such strategies can become fragile when state information from other agents is inaccurate. To this end, we propose a regularized dynamic programming approach for finding sparse feedback policies that selectively depend on the states of a subset of agents in dynamic games. The proposed approach solves convex adaptive group Lasso problems to compute sparse policies approximating Nash equilibrium solutions. We prove the regularized solutions' asymptotic convergence to a neighborhood of Nash equilibrium policies in linear-quadratic (LQ) games. Further, we extend the proposed approach to general nonLQ games via an iterative algorithm. Simulation results in multi-robot interaction scenarios show that the proposed approach effectively computes feedback policies with varying sparsity levels. When agents have noisy observations of other agents' states, simulation results indicate that the proposed regularized policies consistently achieve lower costs than standard Nash equilibrium policies by up to $77 \%$ for all interacting agents whose costs are coupled with other agents' states. ${ }^{1}$


Index Terms—Feedback Nash Equilibrium, Information Sparsity, Noncooperative Dynamic Games

## I. INTRODUCTION

Dynamic game theory models the strategic decisions of multiple interacting agents over time. In such games, it is common to identify solutions at which players execute full state feedback strategies that depend on all players' states. its actions based on the states of other robots. However, obtaining full state information is often expensive or impractical due to sensing and communication limitations. Worse, "dense" strategies that require access to many other agents' states can be brittle when such state information is inaccurate, e.g., in the presence of uncertainties. Consequently, it is desirable for agents to find strategies that selectively depend on the states of a subset of agents while still approximating equilibrium behavior.

We contribute an algorithm for finding sparse feedback policies that depend on fewer influential agents' states in dynamic games while approximating Nash equilibrium strategies. More specifically, we propose a regularized dynamic programming (DP) scheme [1], [2] that approximately solves linear-quadratic (LQ) dynamic games, which are an important extension of the linear-quadratic regulator (LQR) problem [3] to multi-agent interaction settings. The proposed approach solves a convex adaptive group Lasso regularization problem [4] to encode structured sparsity within each DP iteration. A user can choose a desired sparsity level based on the available sensing or communication resources. We also employ an iterative linear-quadratic approximation technique [5], [6] to extend the proposed approach to general non-LQ games.

To establish theoretical properties of the proposed approach, we first derive an upper bound on the deviation of the regularized policy matrix computed by the proposed approach from the Nash equilibrium in a single stage of an LQ game. Then, we prove the asymptotic convergence of the regularized DP recursion to a neighborhood of the Nash equilibrium across all stages of the game.

We test the proposed approach in simulation and support the following key claims: First, the proposed approach yields more sparse feedback strategies than standard Nash equilibrium solutions and thereby requires less communication and sensing resources to execute. Second, the proposed approach yields different levels of sparsity as the user varies the regularization strength. Third, we empirically show that the proposed approach can be readily extended to general non-LQ games via an iterative scheme. Fourth, for all interacting agents whose costs are coupled with other agents' states, the regularized strategies show improved robustness and task performance in comparison to standard Nash equilibria in cases where agents only have inaccurate knowledge of other agents, e.g., noisy estimates of other agents' states.

## II. Related Works
## A. Noncooperative Games

Over the years, a growing body of literature has explored the application of dynamic noncooperative games [1], [7] in designing autonomous systems [5], [8]-[17]. Among different types of games, we focus on general-sum Nash equilibrium problems, where players can have partially competing objectives and make decisions simultaneously. In Nash games with different information patterns, feedback and open-loop Nash equilibrium are the most common solution types. Open-loop Nash equilibria ignore the dynamic, multi-stage nature of the problem by assuming that players choose their entire decision sequences, i.e., trajectories, at once [18]-[22]. In contrast, a feedback Nash equilibrium is a set of control policies that map game states to players' controls; they are more expressive than open-loop solutions but strictly more challenging to compute. Various special cases have been studied, e.g., in [23]-[25], among others. For general feedback games with nonconvex costs and constraints, only approximate solutions exist, e.g., in [5], [6]. We also note that both open-loop and feedback LQ games have well-studied solutions [1], [26].

This work focuses on feedback solutions to LQ dynamic games, where we encourage sparsity structure in the resulting strategies via a regularized DP procedure. We also extend the approach to non-LQ games via an iterative linear-quadratic approximation technique [5].

## B. Structured Controller Design

The literature on encoding sparsity structures into control strategies primarily focuses on single-agent optimal control settings [3] and can generally be categorized into two groups. The first category [27]-[32] requires a predefined sparsity structure, using this as a constraint to compute controls. For instance, each controller may have access only to a subset of the sensing information. More relevant to our work, studies in the second category propose methods to encourage sparsity in classical LQR problems without requiring a predefined sparsity structure [33]-[36]. These approaches introduce sparsity regularizers into the LQR cost, resulting in nonconvex policy optimization problems. Prior works further encourage sparse policies in cooperative Markov games with finite state-action spaces [37] and noncooperative LQ games [38]. Although [38] also studies noncooperative games, it does not consider group sparsity that explicitly reduces inter-agent dependencies; rather, it requires the number of nonzero entries in policy matrices to be specified a priori and as constraints, which does not offer flexibility in balancing between game costs and sparsity level.

Research on finding sparse policies in noncooperative games remains relatively scarce, despite the fact that sparse strategies are especially desirable in reducing inter-agent communication and sensing requirements. To address this gap, our approach encourages group sparsity in the computed control policies, where each group corresponds to the influence of one agent's state on another agent's control action. Given the convergence challenges associated with direct policy optimization in general-sum games, we adopt a modified DP approach.

At each stage, we solve a convex adaptive group Lasso problem [4], [39], an extension of the Lasso problem [40] to variables in pre-specified groups. This modified DP scheme retains convexity and enables formal convergence analysis and extension to more general non-LQ game settings.

A preliminary version of this work has been accepted for presentation at the International Conference on Autonomous Agents and Multiagent Systems, 2025². This manuscript additionally adds theoretical results, proofs, more experimental results, a discussion of related works, and a more detailed presentation of the approach.

## III. PRELIMINARIES

We study noncooperative dynamic games played by $N$ players in discrete time $t \in\{1, \ldots, T\} \equiv[T]$. We first study LQ games in Section IV-A, and then extend to more general non-LQ games in Section IV-B. We define LQ games as the following:

Definition 1: An N-player, general-sum, discrete-time dynamic game is a linear-quadratic (LQ) game if each player $i \in\{1, \ldots, N\} \equiv[N]$ seeks to optimize an individual quadratic cost function:

$$
\begin{aligned}
J^{i}=\frac{1}{2} \sum_{t=1}^{T}\left(\left(x_{t}^{\top} Q_{t}^{i}\right.\right. & \left.\left.+2 q_{t}^{i \top}\right) x_{t}+\sum_{j=1}^{N}\left(u_{t}^{j \top} R_{t}^{i j}+2 r_{t}^{i j \top}\right) u_{t}^{j}\right) \\
& +\frac{1}{2}\left(x_{T+1}^{\top} Q_{T+1}^{i}+2 q_{T+1}^{i \top}\right) x_{T+1}
\end{aligned}
$$

and players follow a joint linear dynamical system:

$$
x_{t+1}=A_{t} x_{t}+\sum_{i=1}^{N} B_{t}^{i} u_{t}^{i}
$$

with $x_{t}^{i} \in \mathbb{R}^{m^{i}}, u_{t}^{i} \in \mathbb{R}^{n^{i}}$, and $Q_{t}^{i} \succeq 0, R_{t}^{i i} \succ 0, \forall i \in[N]$. We let $m=\sum_{i \in[N]} m^{i}$ and $n=\sum_{i \in[N]} n^{i}$. The initial state of the game $x_{1}$ is a given a priori.
Notation. $x \in \mathbb{R}^{m}$ and $u \in \mathbb{R}^{n}$ denote players' states and controls. Superscripts denote players' indices and subscripts are discrete time steps, e.g., $u_{t}^{i} \in \mathbb{R}^{n^{i}}$ denotes player $i$ 's control at time step $t$. Throughout the manuscript, the absence of player and time indices without additional definition denotes concatenation, i.e., $x_{t}:=\left[x_{t}^{1 \top}, x_{t}^{2 \top}, \ldots, x_{t}^{N \top}\right]^{\top}$ and $x^{i}:=$ $\left[x_{1}^{i \top}, x_{2}^{i \top}, \ldots, x_{T}^{i \top}\right]^{\top}$.

In more general non-LQ games discussed in Section IV-B, players follow a joint dynamical system:

$$
x_{t+1}=f_{t}\left(x_{t}, u_{t}^{1}, \ldots, u_{t}^{N}\right)
$$

while optimizing individual costs $J^{i}$ :

$$
\min _{u^{i}} \underbrace{\sum_{t=1}^{T} g_{t}\left(x_{t}, u_{t}^{1}, \ldots, u_{t}^{N}\right)+g_{T+1}\left(x_{T+1}\right)}_{J^{i}\left(u_{1}, \ldots, u_{T}\right)}
$$

consisting of additive stage costs $g_{t}, \forall t \in[T]$ and a terminal cost $g_{T+1}$. The cost functions $J^{i}$ can be nonquadratic and the dynamics $f_{t}$ can be nonlinear functions.

We focus on the solution concept of feedback Nash equilibrium [1, Def. 6.2] defined below.

Definition 2: A feedback Nash equilibrium of an N-player, general-sum, discrete-time dynamic game is an $N$-tuple of strategies $\left\{\gamma^{i *}, i \in[N]\right\}$ with $u_{t}^{i *}=\gamma_{t}^{i *}\left(x_{t}\right)$ that satisfies the following Nash equilibrium conditions $\forall t \in[T], i \in[N]$ for the cost in Eq. (4):

$$
\begin{aligned}
& J^{i}\left(\left(\gamma_{v}^{j}\right)_{j=1, v=1}^{N, t-1},\left(\gamma_{v}^{j *}\right)_{j=1, v=t}^{N, T}\right) \\
& \leq J^{i}(\underbrace{\left(\gamma_{v}^{j}\right)_{j=1, v=1}^{N, t-1}}_{\text {stages }<t} ; \underbrace{\left(\left(\gamma_{v}^{i *}\right)_{j \neq i, v=t}^{T},\left(\left(\gamma_{v}^{i}\right)_{v=t},\left(\gamma_{v}^{i *}\right)_{v=t+1}^{T}\right)\right)}_{\text {stages } \geq t} .)
\end{aligned}
$$

Intuitively, at a feedback Nash equilibrium, each player's strategy is unilaterally optimal from an arbitrary stage $t$ onwards. We note that the standard feedback Nash equilibrium in Definition 2 consists of full-state feedback strategies $\gamma_{t}^{i *}$ that map all players' states to player $i$ 's control $u_{t}^{i *}=\gamma_{t}^{i *}\left(x_{t}\right)$. This work seeks to find regularized feedback Nash equilibrium strategies that approximate standard Nash equilibrium and also are sparse, i.e., depend on fewer agents' states.

## IV. APPROACH

Section IV-A presents the proposed approach to compute regularized feedback Nash equilibria in LQ games, which is the focus of this work. Section IV-B discusses an extension to non-LQ games.

## A. Regularized Dynamic Programming for Linear-Quadratic Games

We first introduce the computation of standard feedback Nash equilibria and then discuss the modification to yield solutions with sparse inter-agent dependencies.

1) Computation of Feedback Nash Equilibrium via DP: We introduce the main results of computing feedback Nash equilibria via DP. For more details, please refer to [1], [41]. A feedback Nash equilibrium solution recursively satisfies the following coupled Hamilton-Jacobi (HJ) equations for value functions $V_{t}^{i}\left(x_{t}\right), \forall i \in[N], t \in[T]$ :

$$
\begin{aligned}
V_{t}^{i}\left(x_{t}\right)= & \min _{u_{t}^{i}} \ell_{t}^{i}\left(x_{t}, u_{t}\right) \\
= & \min _{u_{t}^{i}}\left(\frac{1}{2}\left(x_{t}^{\top} Q_{t}^{i}+2 q_{t}^{i \top}\right) x_{t}+\right. \\
& \left.\frac{1}{2} \sum_{j=1}^{N}\left(u_{t}^{i \top} R_{t}^{i j}+2 r_{t}^{i j \top}\right) u_{t}^{j}+V_{t+1}^{i}\left(x_{t+1}\right)\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where other agents play their Nash equilibrium strategies, i.e., $u_{t}^{j}=\gamma^{j *}\left(x_{t}\right), \forall j \neq i ; V_{T+1}^{i}\left(x_{T+1}\right)$ is equal to the terminal cost $\frac{1}{2}\left(x_{T+1}^{j} Q_{T+1}^{i}+2 q_{T+1}^{i}\right) x_{T+1}$.

The DP procedure goes backwards in time. Under standard assumptions $Q_{t}^{i} \succeq 0, R_{t}^{i i} \succ 0, R_{t}^{i j} \succeq 0, \forall i, j \in[N], i \neq j$, the objective function of each DP iteration is strongly convex, and the feedback Nash equilibrium policy takes an affine form:

$$
u_{t}^{i *}=\gamma_{t}^{i *}\left(x_{t}\right)=-P_{t}^{i} x_{t}-\alpha_{t}^{i}
$$

We refer to $P_{t}^{i}$ as a policy matrix, to which we are interested in encoding group sparsity in Section IV-A.2. The value function takes a quadratic form:

$$
V_{t}^{i}\left(x_{t}\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(x_{t}^{\top} Z_{t}^{i}+2 \eta_{t}^{i \top}\right) x_{t}+\beta_{t}^{i}
$$

with $Z_{t}^{i}, \eta_{t}^{i}, \beta_{t}^{i}$ being defined recursively:

$$
\begin{aligned}
Z_{t}^{i}= & Q_{t}^{i}+\sum_{j=1}^{N} P_{t}^{j \top} R_{t}^{i j} P_{t}^{j}+F_{t}^{\top} Z_{t+1}^{i} F_{t} \\
\eta_{t}^{i}= & q_{t}^{i}+\sum_{j=1}^{N}\left(P_{t}^{j \top} R_{t}^{i j} \alpha_{t}^{i}-P_{t}^{j \top} r_{t}^{i j}\right)+F_{t}^{\top}\left(Z_{t+1}^{i} \omega_{t}+\eta_{t+1}^{i}\right) \\
\beta_{t}^{i}= & \frac{1}{2}\left(\alpha_{t}^{j \top} R_{t}^{i j}-2 r_{t}^{i j \top}\right) \alpha_{t}^{j}+\frac{1}{2}\left(Z_{t+1}^{i} \omega_{t}+\right. \\
& \left.2 \eta_{t+1}^{i}\right)^{\top} \omega_{t}+\beta_{t+1}^{i}
\end{aligned}
$$

where:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& F_{t}=A_{t}-\sum_{j=1}^{N} B_{t}^{j} P_{t}^{j}, \omega_{t}=-\sum_{j=1}^{N} B_{t}^{j} \alpha_{t}^{j} \\
& Z_{T+1}^{i}=Q_{T+1}^{i}, \eta_{T+1}^{i}=q_{T+1}^{i}
\end{aligned}
$$

We refer to $Z_{t}^{i}$ as a value matrix.
At each DP stage, a Nash equilibrium policy can be computed via solving coupled Riccati equations to compute $P_{t}, \alpha_{t}$ :

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left(R_{t}^{i i}+B_{t}^{i \top} Z_{t+1}^{i} B_{t}^{i}\right) P_{t}^{i}+B_{t}^{i \top} Z_{t+1}^{i} \sum_{j \neq i} B_{t}^{j} P_{t}^{j}=B_{t}^{i \top} Z_{t+1}^{i} A_{t} \\
& \left(R_{t}^{i i}+B_{t}^{i \top} Z_{t+1}^{i} B_{t}^{i}\right) \alpha_{t}^{i}+B_{t}^{i \top} Z_{t+1}^{i} \sum_{j \neq i} B_{t}^{j} \alpha_{t}^{j}=B_{t}^{i \top} \eta_{t+1}^{i}+r_{t}^{i i}
\end{aligned}
$$

We rewrite Eq. (10a) in a matrix form $S_{t} P_{t}=Y_{t}$, which we shall use in Section IV-A.2:

$$
S_{t} P_{t}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
B_{t}^{1 \top} Z_{t+1}^{1} A_{t} \\
B_{t}^{2 \top} Z_{t+1}^{2} A_{t} \\
\ldots \\
B_{t}^{N \top} Z_{t+1}^{N} A_{t}
\end{array}\right]
$$

with $P_{t}=\left[P_{t}^{1 \top}, \ldots, P_{t}^{N \top}\right]^{\top}$ and $S_{t}$ being defined as:

$$
S_{t}=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
R_{t}^{11}+B_{t}^{1 \top} Z_{t+1}^{1} B_{t}^{1} & \ldots & B_{t}^{1 \top} Z_{t+1}^{1} B_{t}^{N} \\
B_{t}^{2 \top} Z_{t+1}^{2} B_{t}^{1} & \ldots & B_{t}^{2 \top} Z_{t+1}^{2} B_{t}^{N} \\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\
B_{t}^{N \top} Z_{t+1}^{N} B_{t}^{1} & \ldots & R_{t}^{N N}+B_{t}^{N \top} Z_{t+1}^{N} B_{t}^{N}
\end{array}\right]
$$

2) Regularization: At each DP stage, solving the system in Eq. (11) exactly computes the feedback parts of the standard Nash equilibrium strategies. To compute sparse policies $P_{t}$, we propose to solve a regularized problem:

$$
\min _{\hat{P}_{t}} \frac{1}{2}\left\|S_{t} \hat{P}_{t}-Y_{t}\right\|_{F}^{2}+\sum_{i, j} \lambda_{i, j}\left\|\hat{P}_{t}^{i}[j]\right\|_{F}
$$

where $\|\cdot\|_{F}$ denotes matrix Frobenius norm and $\hat{P}_{t}^{i[j]}$ denotes a block in the policy matrix that maps the $j^{\text {th }}$ player's states to the $i^{\text {th }}$ player's controls. For example, in a 4-player game,

a policy matrix $P_{t}$ or $\hat{P}_{t}$ shown via a heatmap in Fig. 1 is divided into $4 \times 4$ blocks. Throughout the manuscript, we use a hat notation to denote quantities computed in the recursion with policy sparsity regularization, e.g., $\hat{P}_{t}, \hat{Z}_{t}, \lambda_{i, j}$ denotes a weighting constant that determines the regularization strength for block $(i, j)$. Setting $\lambda_{i, j}=0, \forall i, j \in[N]$ recovers a standard feedback Nash equilibrium solution. For a block $(i, j)$, as the user increases $\lambda_{i, j}$, the values in the block are penalized more until the entire block is "zeroed out". We note that we choose $\lambda_{i, i}=0, \forall i \in[N]$ and $\lambda_{i, j}=\lambda, \forall i \neq j, \lambda \in \mathbb{R}_{\geq 0}$, to not discourage the players' strategies from depending on their own states and to penalize other blocks evenly. Hence, by solving the problem in Eq. (12), the computed policy can automatically choose to depend on fewer agents' states. Solving the problem in Eq. (12) can be interpreted as solving the problem in Eq. (6) with sparsity regularization.

The problem in Eq. (12) is a group Lasso problem, which was initially proposed in [39] and has been extended and widely applied to grouped variable selection, e.g., in highdimensional statistics [42] and signal processing [43]. More specifically in our case, since $\lambda_{i, i}=0, \forall i \in[N]$ in Eq. (12), our problem is termed an adaptive group Lasso problem [42, Ch.4].

Importantly, the problem in Eq. (12) encourages sparsity in the solution at a group level. The entries in a group all remain non-zero or get zeroed out together. The problem is convex, and can be solved using established algorithms for group Lasso, e.g., via block coordinate descent [39], [42], [44] or a projected gradient method [45]. We also show in Appendix that this problem can be cast as a conic program and effectively solved via off-the-shelf conic optimization solvers.

Hence, at each dynamic programming iteration $t$ described in Section IV-A.1, instead of solving the system in Eq. (11) exactly, we solve the problem in Eq. (12) to compute regularized Nash equilibrium strategies. Using the regularized strategies $\hat{\gamma}_{t}^{i *}$, we then compute value functions $\hat{V}_{t}^{i}\left(x_{t}\right)$ that correspond to state values for the sparse policies. We repeat this process backwards for every stage $t \in[T]$.

Remark 1: Note that our approach in Eq. (12) regularizes a specific step in the DP associated with LQ feedback games and maintains convexity at each step. In contrast, prior efforts [33]-[36] (in the single-agent context) regularize the entire policy optimization objective and solve a nonconvex problem. In general, extending direct policy optimization methods to general-sum games can face convergence challenges [46].
3) Convergence of the Regularized Dynamic Program: In this section, we analyze the convergence of the proposed DP scheme on the regularized policy matrix $\hat{P}_{t}$ and value matrix $\hat{Z}_{t}$ to a neighborhood of the Nash equilibrium.

We denote an unregularized solution to the system in Eq. (11) as $P_{t}$ and a regularized solution to the problem in Eq. (12) as $\hat{P}_{t}$. We define the difference between the two solutions as $\Delta P_{t}:=\hat{P}_{t}-P_{t}$. We also denote the minimum singular value of a matrix as $\sigma_{\min (\cdot)}$. When we consider the asymptotic behavior of finite-horizon games, we shall fix the horizon $T$ as a finite constant and allow $t \downarrow-\infty$.

We refer to the recursion on the value matrix $Z_{t}^{i}$ in Eq. (9) as "unregularized coupled Riccati recursion". The proposed
approach instead solves a regularized problem in Eq. (12) at each iteration and therefore yields a "regularized coupled Riccati recursion":

$$
\hat{Z}_{t}^{i}=Q^{i}+\sum_{j=1}^{N} \hat{P}_{t}^{j \top} R^{i j} \hat{P}_{t}^{j}+\hat{F}_{t}^{\top} \hat{Z}_{t+1}^{i} \hat{F}_{t}
$$

where $\hat{F}_{t}=F_{t}-\sum_{j=1}^{N} B^{j} \Delta P_{t}^{j}$. This section analyzes the difference between the regularized and unregularized Riccati recursions. Note that the analysis will also use the notion of "infinite-horizon coupled Riccati equation":

$$
Z^{i *}=Q^{i}+\sum_{j=1}^{N} P^{j * \top} R^{i j} P^{j *}+F^{* \top} Z^{i *} F^{*}
$$

which is defined similarly as Eq. (9) but for settings when the horizon of the game in Definition 1 is infinite. With a slight abuse of notation, we note that here the absence of subscript denotes that the value of $Z^{i *}$ is static across time. In the analysis in this section, we focus on the settings where the problem data, i.e. the collection $\left(Q_{t}^{i}, q_{t}^{i}, R_{t}^{i j}, r_{t}^{i j}\right)_{i, j \in[N], t \leq T+1}$, for the game in Definition 1 are time-invariant, which is standard when analyzing convergence of Riccati recursions [1, Ch.6] and holds true for all of our experimental examples in Section V.

We first analyze and bound the difference between solving the regularized problem in Eq. (12) compared to solving the system in Eq. (11) exactly for a single stage. However, tracking the differences propagated through the Riccati recursion in Eq. (13) is generally challenging. We therefore take a dynamical system perspective and prove that under certain mild conditions, the regularized Riccati recursion converges to a neighborhood of the unregularized Riccati recursion, i.e., the regularization does not cause a diverging error. Under a mild assumption, the single-step $\Delta P_{t}$ can be explicitly upper bounded.

Assumption 1: We assume that the unregularized game in Definition 1 has a unique Nash equilibrium, i.e., $S_{t}$ in Eq. (11) is invertible.

This assumption is mild and is a common setup in the literature [1, Ch.6]. In our experiments in Section V, we do not have an issue satisfying this invertibility requirement of $S_{t}$.

Lemma 1: Let Assumption 1 hold and let $P_{t}$ solve Eq. (11) and $\hat{P}_{t}$ solve the problem in Eq. (12) with the same problem data $S_{t}, Y_{t}$. Then, the difference $\Delta P_{t}$ between $\hat{P}_{t}$ and $P_{t}$ can be upper bounded as:

$$
\left\|\Delta P_{t}\right\|_{F} \leq \frac{\sum_{i, j \in[N]} \lambda_{i, j}}{\sigma_{\min }^{2}\left(S_{t}\right)}
$$

By Assumption 1, the original game in Definition 1 has a unique solution, $S_{t}$ in Eq. (11) is of full rank and has positive singular values. Hence, the upper bound in Eq. (15) is finite when $\lambda_{i, j}<\infty$ for all $i, j \in[N]$. We prove Lemma 1 by casting the problem of solving Eq. (11) as a least-squares optimization problem and compare the optimality conditions of the unregularized problem and the nonsmooth regularized problem. We give the complete proof in Appendix.

Lemma 1 provides a bound on $\Delta P_{t}$ that shrinks to zero as $\lambda$ decreases. While Lemma 1 accounts for the situation where the problem data $S_{t}, Y_{t}$ are the same for the unregularized and regularized problems, this is not the case when the difference caused by regularization propagates through the coupled Riccati recursion in Eq. (13). That is, the regularized DP recursion will ultimately have problem data $\hat{S}_{t}, \hat{Y}_{t}$ that are different from the unregularized system in Eq. (11). Under another mild assumption, we can overcome this challenge by leveraging dynamical system theory.
Assumption 2: We assume that the steady-state matrix $Z^{*}$ in Eq. (14) is a locally asymptotically stable (LAS) fixed point of the finite-horizon Riccati recursion for $Z_{t}$ in Eq. (9). The absence of the superscripts denotes aggregation over all the players.
By Assumption 2, $Z_{t}$ in Eq. (9) locally converges to $Z^{*}$ in Eq. (14) at the limit $t \rightarrow-\infty$. This requirement is not restrictive, as taking the limit of the finite-horizon Riccati sequence is a common approach to finding Nash equilibria for infinite-horizon LQ games [1, Ch.6]. Specific conditions to guarantee that the infinite-horizon Riccati solution is a LAS fixed point can be obtained for LQR and zero-sum LQ games, but it is challenging to get such conditions for general-sum LQ games [1, Ch.6].
We define the difference between Eq. (9) and Eq. (14) as a dynamical system $\tilde{Z}_{t}:=Z_{t}-Z^{*}=\tau\left(\tilde{Z}_{t+1}, 0\right)$ with zero input and the origin as a LAS point. Regularization using the proposed scheme in Eq. (12) injects a disturbance $\delta_{t}=$ $\Delta P_{t}$ to the system at each stage and yields a perturbed system $\hat{\tilde{Z}}_{t}=\tau\left(\hat{\tilde{Z}}_{t+1}, \delta_{t}\right)$, which corresponds to the difference between Eq. (13) and Eq. (14). To this end, we provide the following theorem and corollary.
Theorem 1: Let Assumption 1 and Assumption 2 hold. Then, the dynamical system $\hat{\tilde{Z}}_{t}=\tau\left(\hat{\tilde{Z}}_{t+1}, \delta_{t}\right)$, with the difference $\hat{\tilde{Z}}_{t}:=\tilde{Z}_{t}-Z^{*}$ being the state and the policy deviation $\Delta P_{t}$ caused by regularization in Eq. (12) as disturbances $\delta_{t}$, is locally input-to-state stable (ISS). That is, there exist a class $\mathcal{K} \mathcal{L}$ function $\beta$ and a class $\mathcal{K}$ function $\rho$ such that:

$$
\left\|\hat{\tilde{Z}}_{t}\right\|_{F} \leq \beta\left(\left\|\hat{\tilde{Z}}_{T+1}\right\|_{F}, T-t\right)+\rho\left(\left\|\delta_{t}\right\|_{\infty}\right), \forall t \in(-\infty, T]
$$

for disturbances such that $\sup _{t \leq \tau \leq T}\left\|\delta_{\tau}\right\|_{F}=\left\|\delta_{t}\right\|_{\infty}<\delta, \delta \in$ $\mathbb{R}_{>0}$ and $\left\|\hat{\tilde{Z}}_{T+1}\right\|_{F} \leq z, z \in \mathbb{R}_{>0}$.
Corollary 1: Let Assumption 1 and Assumption 2 hold and $\left\|\hat{\tilde{Z}}_{T+1}\right\|_{F} \leq z, z \in \mathbb{R}_{>0}$. Then, for all $\epsilon>0$, there exists $\xi>0$, such that for all $\lambda_{i, j}$ satisfying $\sum_{i, j \in[N]} \lambda_{i, j} \leq \xi$, the regularized coupled Riccati recursion approaches the ball with radius $\epsilon$ :

$$
\limsup _{t \rightarrow-\infty}\left\|\tilde{Z}_{t}-Z^{*}\right\|_{F} \leq \epsilon
$$

Remark 2: Given the convergence of $\tilde{Z}_{t}^{i}$, the convergence of $\hat{P}_{t}$ also follows. Particularly, from Eq. (11), we notice that $S_{t}$ and $Y_{t}$ both depend linearly on $Z_{t+1}^{i}$ and Eq. (11) is a linear system of equations with respect to $P_{t}$. Therefore, one can relate the ultimate bound of $\left\|\hat{P}_{t}-P^{*}\right\|_{F}$ back to the ultimate bound of $\left\|\hat{\tilde{Z}}_{t}\right\|_{F}$ in Eq. (17) using linear system perturbation theory [47, Ch.6] and the bound in Lemma 1.

We provide a complete proof of Theorem 1 and Corollary 1 in the Appendix. Theorem 1 and Corollary 1 suggest that the regularized Riccati recursion will converge to a neighborhood of the infinite-horizon Riccati equation under bounded disturbances caused by the regularization. Our analysis shows the asymptotic tradeoff between players' costs and policy sparsity, and ensures that the difference in cost-to-go induced by the group-sparsity regularization of Eq. (12) is bounded under bounded regularization weights $\sum_{i, j \in[N]} \lambda_{i, j} \leq \xi$. For large regularization such that $\sum_{i, j \in[N]} \lambda_{i, j}>\xi$, we also empirically observe convergence of the Riccati recursion in Section VB. Our conjecture is that the sparsity regularization added to off-diagonal blocks in policy matrices causes the regularized Riccati recursion to be more "decoupled" between players and the dynamical system $\hat{\tilde{Z}}_{t}=\tau\left(\hat{\tilde{Z}}_{t+1}, \delta_{t}\right)$ to be more stable. However, a more detailed analysis is out of the scope of this work. We also empirically show the convergent behaviors for the unregularized and regularized Riccati recursions in Section V-B.

## B. Non-LQ Dynamic Games

The proposed approach focuses on LQ dynamic games. Nonetheless, our DP-based scheme makes it possible to extend to non-LQ games, i.e., settings where players can have nonquadratic costs and nonlinear dynamics. We employ an iterative algorithm [5] shown in Algorithm 1 that repeatedly finds LQ approximations of the original dynamic game and solves the approximating LQ games with regularization in Eq. (12) to obtain sparse, approximate feedback Nash equilibrium strategies. This type of iterative LQ algorithm has been studied in the context of standard (unregularized) feedback Nash games [5], [6], [48], and in [6] it is shown that fixed points of these algorithms approximately satisfy the firstorder optimality conditions for all players which correspond to the feedback Nash equilibrium concept in Definition 2. We do not provide convergence results for non-LQ games. For a more detailed analysis of convergence and open challenges, please refer to [6].

## VI. CONCLUSION

We have presented a regularized DP approach for finding sparse feedback policies in noncooperative games. The regularized policies selectively depend on a subset of agents' states, thereby reducing the communication and sensing resources required for execution. The proposed approach encodes structured sparsity into LQ game solutions via solving a convex adaptive group Lasso problem at each DP iteration. This approach is further extended to general non-LQ games via iterative LQ approximations.

For LQ games, we establish an upper bound on the singlestage difference between the regularized and standard Nash equilibrium policy matrices. Thus equipped, we prove the asymptotic convergence of the regularized solution to a neighborhood of the Nash equilibrium across all game stages.

Extensive results in multi-robot navigation tasks validate the efficacy of the proposed approach in producing sparse feedback policies at varying regularization levels and demonstrate its scalability to games involving multiple players. Monte

Carlo studies in a multi-agent formation game also show that when interacting agents with coupled costs have noisy observations of other agents' states, it is always better to employ some (nonzero) degree of regularization. In this case, the regularized policies consistently outperform standard Nash equilibrium solutions by selectively ignoring information that may be inaccurate.

Future work could explore the optimal selection of regularization strengths across different game stages. Additionally, applying the proposed regularization scheme to scenarios involving more complex uncertainties beyond observation noise is also an interesting direction. Lastly, a deeper investigation into the observation presented in Section V-A-where our approach yields distinct local solutions at different regularization levels in non-LQ games-would be of interest.

Proof of Lemma 1. We rewrite the unregularized system of equations in Eq. (11) as an optimization problem:

$$
\min _{\hat{P}_{t}} \underbrace{\frac{1}{2}\left\|S_{t} P_{t}-Y_{t}\right\|_{F}^{2}}_{h\left(P_{t}\right)},
$$

and we have the regularized problem in Eq. (12):

$$
\min _{\hat{P}_{t}} \hat{h}\left(\hat{P}_{t}\right)=\underbrace{\frac{1}{2}\left\|S_{t} \hat{P}_{t}-Y_{t}\right\|_{F}^{2}}_{h\left(\hat{P}_{t}\right)}+\underbrace{\sum_{i, j} \lambda_{i, j}\left\|\hat{P}_{t}^{i}[j]\right\|_{F}}_{\psi\left(\hat{P}_{t}\right)},
$$

where $\hat{P}_{t}^{i}[j] \in \mathbb{R}^{n^{i} \times m^{j}}$ denotes the $(i, j)$ block of the $\hat{P}_{t}$ matrix. We recall the dimensions of players' states and controls $x_{t}^{i} \in \mathbb{R}^{m^{i}}, u_{t}^{i} \in \mathbb{R}^{n^{i}}$, and $m=\sum_{i \in[N]} m^{i}, n=$ $\sum_{i \in[N]} n^{i}$. Hence, we have $S_{t} \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times n}$, and $P_{t}, \hat{P}_{t} \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times m}$.

First, we examine the optimality conditions for both problems and characterize their solutions. Then, we bound the difference between the two solutions.

Optimality conditions: The unregularized problem in Eq. (18) is a convex optimization problem with a differentiable objective function, whose necessary and sufficient optimality condition [50, Ch.4] is:

$$
\nabla_{P_{t}} h\left(P_{t}\right)=0 \Rightarrow M_{t} P_{t}-S_{t}^{\top} Y_{t}=0 \Rightarrow P_{t}=M_{t}^{-1} S_{t}^{\top} Y_{t}
$$

where we define $M_{t}=S_{t}^{\top} S_{t}$ and recall that $S_{t}$ is full rank by Assumption 1.

The objective of the regularized problem in Eq. (19) is nonsmooth but convex. Since $h$ is convex and differentiable and $\psi$ is convex and finite-valued, we have the necessary and sufficient optimality condition [51, Thm 8.17]:

$$
\begin{aligned}
0 \in \nabla_{\hat{P}_{t}} h\left(\hat{P}_{t}\right) & +\partial_{\hat{P}_{t}} \psi\left(\hat{P}_{t}\right) \\
& =M_{t} \hat{P}_{t}-S_{t}^{\top} Y_{t}+\partial_{\hat{P}_{t}}\left(\sum_{i, j} \lambda_{i, j}\left\|\hat{P}_{t}^{i}[j]\right\|_{F}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\partial(\cdot)$ denotes the subdifferential set. Since $\psi$ is convex and finite-valued [51, Thm 8.11], we have:

$$
\partial_{\hat{P}_{t}} \psi=\partial_{\hat{P}_{t}}\left(\sum_{i, j} \lambda_{i, j}\left\|\hat{P}_{t}^{i}[j]\right\|_{F}\right)=\sum_{i, j} \lambda_{i, j} \partial_{\hat{P}_{t}}\left(\left\|\hat{P}_{t}^{i}[j]\right\|_{F}\right)
$$

Therefore, we obtain the optimality condition:

$$
0 \in M_{t} \hat{P}_{t}-S_{t}^{\top} Y_{t}+\sum_{i, j} \lambda_{i, j} \partial_{\hat{P}_{t}}\left(\left\|\hat{P}_{t}^{i}[j]\right\|_{F}\right)
$$

The subdifferential for $\left\|\hat{P}_{t}^{i}[j]\right\|_{F}$ is given by:

$$
\partial_{\hat{P}_{t}^{i}[j]}\left(\left\|\hat{P}_{t}^{i}[j]\right\|_{F}\right)= \begin{cases}\frac{\hat{P}_{t}^{i}[j]}{\left\|\hat{P}_{t}^{i}[j]\right\|_{F}}, \hat{P}_{t}^{i}[j] \neq 0 \\ \left\{z \left\lvert\, z \in \mathbb{R}^{n^{i} \times m^{j}},\|z\|_{F} \leq 1\right\}, \hat{P}_{t}^{i}[j]=0\right.\end{cases}
$$

Therefore, elements in the subdifferential $\partial_{\hat{P}_{t}}\left(\left\|\hat{P}_{t}^{i}[j]\right\|_{F}\right)$ are matrices that have entries shown in Eq. (22) for block $(i, j)$ and zeros elsewhere.

For a solution $\hat{P}_{t}$ that satisfies the optimality condition in Eq. (21), we must be able to find a particular set of subgradients $\theta_{1,1}^{*}, \theta_{1,2}^{*}, \ldots, \theta_{N, N}^{*}$ from the subdifferential sets such that:

$$
0=M_{t} \hat{P}_{t}-S_{t}^{\top} Y_{t}+\sum_{i, j} \lambda_{i, j} \theta_{i, j}^{*}
$$

where $\theta_{i, j}^{*} \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times m}, \theta_{i, j}^{*} \in \partial_{\hat{P}_{t}}\left(\left\|\hat{P}_{t}^{i}[j]\right\|_{F}\right)$. Such a point specifies a solution for the regularized problem, i.e.

$$
\hat{P}_{t}=M_{t}^{-1} S_{t}^{\top} Y_{t}-\sum_{i, j} \lambda_{i, j} M_{t}^{-1} \theta_{i, j}^{*}
$$

Bounding the solution difference: Having characterized solutions to the two problems in Eqs. (18) and (19), we summarize Eq. (20) and Eq. (23) to compute the difference between the solutions:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left\|\Delta P_{t}\right\|_{F}=\left\|\hat{P}_{t}-P_{t}\right\|_{F}=\| & \sum_{i, j} \lambda_{i, j} M_{t}^{-1} \theta_{i, j}^{*}\|_{F} \\
& \leq \sum_{i, j} \lambda_{i, j}\left\|M_{t}^{-1} \theta_{i, j}^{*}\right\|_{F}
\end{aligned}
$$

Next, we split the terms in $\sum_{i, j} \lambda_{i, j}\left\|M_{t}^{-1} \theta_{i, j}^{*}\right\|_{F}$ into two cases based on Eq. (22).

Case 1. For blocks $(i, j)$ such that $\hat{P}_{t}^{i}[j] \neq 0$, we have that $\left\|\hat{\theta}_{i, j}^{*}\right\|_{F}=1$. We denote a vectorization operator as $\operatorname{vec}(\cdot)$. We note that we can rewrite the multiplication $M_{t}^{-1} \theta_{i, j}^{*}$ in a matrix-vector form such that $\left\|\tilde{M}_{t}^{-1} \tilde{\theta}_{i, j}^{*}\right\|_{2}=\left\|M_{t}^{-1} \theta_{i, j}^{*}\right\|_{F}$, where the matrix $\tilde{M}_{t}^{-1}:=\operatorname{blogdiag}\left(M_{t}^{-1}, \ldots, M_{t}^{-1}\right) \in$ $\mathbb{R}^{m n \times m n}$ is the block diagonal concatenation of $m$ copies of $M_{t}^{-1}$, and $\hat{\theta}_{i, j}^{*}:=\operatorname{vec}\left(\theta_{i, j}\right) \in \mathbb{R}^{m n}$.

From the definition of the matrix spectral norm, we have:

$$
\left\|\tilde{M}_{t}^{-1}\right\|_{2}=\sup _{\left\|\hat{\theta}_{i, j}^{*}\right\|_{2}=1}\left\|\tilde{M}_{t}^{-1} \tilde{\theta}_{i, j}^{*}\right\|_{2}
$$

Hence,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\lambda_{i, j}\left\|M_{t}^{-1} \theta_{i, j}^{*}\right\|_{F} & =\lambda_{i, j}\left\|\tilde{M}_{t}^{-1} \tilde{\theta}_{i, j}^{*}\right\|_{2} \\
& \leq \lambda_{i, j}\left\|\tilde{M}_{t}^{-1}\right\|_{2}=\lambda_{i, j} \sigma_{\max }\left(\tilde{M}_{t}^{-1}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\sigma$ denotes singular values. We note that, since $\tilde{M}_{t}$ has a block-diagonal structure, it is straightforward to verify that $\sigma_{\max }\left(\tilde{M}_{t}^{-1}\right)=\sigma_{\max }\left(M_{t}^{-1}\right)$.

Case 2. For blocks $(i, j)$ such that $\hat{P}_{t}^{i}[j]=0$, since we know $\left\|\hat{\theta}_{i, j}^{*}\right\|_{2} \leq 1$, we have:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left\|M_{t}^{-1} \theta_{i, j}^{*}\right\|_{F}=\left\|\tilde{M}_{t}^{-1} \tilde{\theta}_{i, j}^{*}\right\|_{2} & \leq \sup _{\left\|\hat{\theta}_{i, j}^{*}\right\|_{2} \leq 1}\left\|\tilde{M}_{t}^{-1} \hat{\theta}_{i, j}^{*}\right\|_{2} \\
& \leq \sup _{\left\|\hat{\theta}_{i, j}^{*}\right\|_{2}=1}\left\|\tilde{M}_{t}^{-1} \hat{\theta}_{i, j}^{*}\right\|_{2} \\
& =\left\|\tilde{M}_{t}^{-1}\right\|_{2} \\
& =\sigma_{\max }\left(\tilde{M}_{t}^{-1}\right) \\
& =\sigma_{\max }\left(M_{t}^{-1}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Recall that we require the original system of equations in Eq. (11) to have a unique solution, i.e., $S_{t}$ has full rank. Therefore, $M_{t}$ has positive singular values and it follows that $\sigma_{\max }\left(M_{t}^{-1}\right)=\frac{1}{\sigma_{\min }\left(M_{t}\right)}=\frac{1}{\sigma_{\min}^{*}\left(S_{t}\right)}$. Hence, summarizing the two cases,

$$
\left\|\Delta P_{t}\right\|_{F} \leq \frac{\sum_{i, j \in[N]} \lambda_{i, j}}{\sigma_{\min }^{2}\left(S_{t}\right)}
$$

bounds the difference between the regularized and unregularized solutions at a single time step $t$.

Proof of Theorem 1. We first define the dynamical system $\dot{\tilde{Z}}_{t}=\tau\left(\dot{\tilde{Z}}_{t+1}, \delta_{t}\right)$ studied in Theorem 1 and then prove Theorem 1.

Definition of the Dynamical System: For all $i \in[N]$, we have algebraic coupled Riccati equations in Eq. (14) for infinitehorizon LQ game:

$$
Z^{i *}=Q^{i}+\sum_{j=1}^{N} P^{j * \top} R^{i j} P^{j *}+F^{* \top} Z^{i *} F^{*}
$$

For finite-horizon LQ games, we have unregularized coupled Riccati recursion Eq. (9):

$$
Z_{t}^{i}=Q^{i}+\sum_{j=1}^{N} P_{t}^{j \top} R^{i j} P_{t}^{j}+F_{t}^{\top} Z_{t+1}^{i} F_{t}
$$

and regularized coupled Riccati recursion in Eq. (13):

$$
\hat{Z}_{t}^{i}=Q^{i}+\sum_{j=1}^{N} \hat{P}_{t}^{j \top} R^{i j} \hat{P}_{t}^{j}+\hat{F}_{t}^{\top} \hat{Z}_{t+1}^{i} \hat{F}_{t}
$$

where:

$$
\hat{P}_{t}^{j}=P_{t}^{j}+\Delta P_{t}^{j}, \quad \hat{F}_{t}=F_{t}-\sum_{j=1}^{N} B^{j} \Delta P_{t}^{j}
$$

In order to study the convergence of the regularized coupled Riccati recursion, we analyze the asymptotic difference between Eq. (31) and Eq. (29), for all $i \in[N]$ :

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \dot{\tilde{Z}}_{t}^{i}:=\hat{Z}_{t}^{i}-Z^{i *}=\sum_{j=1}^{N} \hat{P}_{t}^{j \top} R^{i j} \hat{P}_{t}^{j}+\hat{F}_{t}^{\top} \hat{Z}_{t+1}^{i} \hat{F}_{t}- \\
& \sum_{j=1}^{N} P^{j * \top} R^{i j} P^{j *}-F^{* \top} Z^{i *} F^{*} \\
&=\sum_{j=1}^{N}\left(P_{t}^{j}+\Delta P_{t}^{j}\right)^{\top} R^{i j}\left(P_{t}^{j}+\Delta P_{t}^{j}\right)+\left(F_{t}-\sum_{j=1}^{N} B^{j} \Delta P_{t}^{j}\right)^{\top} \\
& \quad \hat{Z}_{t+1}^{i}\left(F_{t}-\sum_{k=1}^{N} B^{k} \Delta P_{t}^{k}\right)-\sum_{j=1}^{N} P^{j * \top} R^{i j} P^{j *}-F^{* \top} Z^{i *} F^{*} \\
&=\sum_{j=1}^{N} P_{t}^{j \top} R^{i j} P_{t}^{j}+F_{t}^{\top} \hat{Z}_{t+1}^{i} F_{t}-\sum_{j=1}^{N} P^{j * \top} R^{i j} P^{j *}- \\
& F^{* \top} Z^{i *} F^{*} \\
&+\sum_{j=1}^{N} \Delta P_{t}^{j \top} R^{i j} P_{t}^{j}+\sum_{j=1}^{N} \Delta P_{t}^{j \top} R^{i j} \Delta P_{t}^{j}+\sum_{j=1}^{N} P_{t}^{j \top} R^{i j} \Delta P_{t}^{j} \\
&-\sum_{j=1}^{N} \Delta P_{t}^{j \top} B^{j \top} \hat{Z}_{t+1}^{i} F_{t}-F_{t}^{\top} \hat{Z}_{t+1}^{i} \sum_{k=1}^{N} B^{k} \Delta P_{t}^{k} \\
&+\sum_{j=1}^{N} \Delta P_{t}^{j \top} B^{j \top} \hat{Z}_{t+1}^{i} \sum_{k=1}^{N} B^{k} \Delta P_{t}^{k} \\
&=\phi^{i}\left(\hat{Z}_{t+1}\right)+O^{i}\left(\hat{Z}_{t+1}, \Delta P_{t}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Hence:

$$
\dot{\tilde{Z}}_{t}^{i}=\hat{Z}_{t}^{i}-Z^{i *}=\phi^{i}\left(\hat{Z}_{t+1}\right)+O^{i}\left(\hat{Z}_{t+1}, \Delta P_{t}\right)
$$

Aggregating all the players $\dot{\tilde{Z}}_{t}:=\left[\dot{\tilde{Z}}_{t}^{1 \top}, \ldots, \dot{\tilde{Z}}_{t}^{N \top}\right]^{\top}$, we have:

$$
\dot{\tilde{Z}}_{t}=\hat{Z}_{t}-Z^{*}=\phi\left(\hat{Z}_{t+1}\right)+O\left(\hat{Z}_{t+1}, \Delta P_{t}\right)
$$

We define the dynamical system in Eq. (34) as:

$$
\dot{\tilde{Z}}_{t}=\tau\left(\dot{\tilde{Z}}_{t+1}, \delta_{t}\right)
$$

where we denote regularization difference $\Delta P_{t}$ as disturbance $\delta_{t}$. The system in Eq. (35) is the dynamical system we referred to in Theorem 1.

Proof of Theorem 1: In Eq. (35), the system dynamics $\tau\left(\dot{\tilde{Z}}_{t+1}, \delta_{t}\right)$ consist of the nominal part $\phi\left(\tilde{Z}_{t+1}\right)$ and the part which directly depends upon disturbances $O\left(\tilde{Z}_{t+1}, \Delta P_{t}\right)$, as expanded in Appendix . When there is no regularization, i.e., $\Delta P_{t}=0$ and $\tilde{Z}_{t}=Z_{t}, \forall t$, we have $O\left(\tilde{Z}_{t+1}, \Delta P_{t}\right)=0$ and the system $\dot{\tilde{Z}}_{t}=\tau\left(\dot{\tilde{Z}}_{t+1}, \delta_{t}\right)$ reduces to $\tilde{Z}_{t}=\tau\left(\tilde{Z}_{t+1}, 0\right)$, which only has the nominal part and is exactly the difference between Eq. (30) and Eq. (29) aggregated over all the players. That is, at zero regularization, the dynamical system in Eq. (35) reduces to the difference between the unregularized finitehorizon Riccati and infinite-horizon Riccati equations.

(35) with zero regularization $\tilde{Z}_{t}=\tau\left(\tilde{Z}_{t+1}, 0\right)=\phi\left(\tilde{Z}_{t+1}\right)$ is locally asymptotically stable at the origin. Furthermore, the system in Eq. (35) is continuous in both value matrix $\tilde{Z}_{t+1}$ and disturbance $\Delta P_{t}$, and therefore in $\dot{\tilde{Z}}_{t+1}$ and $\delta_{t}$. Hence, the system in Eq. (35) is locally ISS with respect to the regularization [52, Lemma 2.2].

We recall the definitions of class $\mathcal{K}$ and class $\mathcal{K} \mathcal{L}$ functions [53]:
Definition 3: A continuous function $\rho: \mathbb{R}_{\geq 0} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}_{\geq 0}$ belongs to class $\mathcal{K}$ if it is strictly increasing with $\rho(0)=0$. A continuous function $\beta: \mathbb{R}_{\geq 0} \times \mathbb{R}_{\geq 0} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}_{\geq 0}$ belongs to class $\mathcal{K} \mathcal{L}$ if $\beta(\cdot, k)$ is of class $\mathcal{K}$ for each fixed $k$, and $\beta(r, \cdot)$ is decreasing for each fixed $r$, and $\lim _{k \rightarrow \infty} \beta(r, k)=0$.

From the definition of local input-to-state stability [52, Definition 2.1], there exist a class $\mathcal{K} \mathcal{L}$ function $\beta$ and a class $\mathcal{K}$ function $\rho$ such that:

$$
\left\|\dot{\tilde{Z}}_{t}\right\|_{F} \leq \beta\left(\left\|\dot{\tilde{Z}}_{T+1}\right\|_{F}, T-t\right)+\rho\left(\left\|\delta_{t}\right\|_{\infty}\right), \forall t \in(-\infty, T]
$$

for disturbances such that $\sup _{t \leq r \leq T}\left\|\delta_{r}\right\|_{F}=\left\|\delta_{t}\right\|_{\infty}<\delta, \delta \in$ $\mathbb{R}_{>0}$, and $\left\|\dot{\tilde{Z}}_{T+1}\right\|_{F} \leq z, z \in \mathbb{R}_{>0}$.

$$
\left\|\tilde{Z}_{t}\right\|_{F} \leq \frac{\epsilon}{2}+\rho\left(\left\|\delta_{t}\right\|_{\infty}\right), \forall t \in\left(-\infty, t^{*}\right]
$$

In addition, because $\rho\left(\left\|\delta_{t}\right\|_{\infty}\right)$ is class $\mathcal{K}$, for an arbitrary ball with radius $\epsilon>0$, there exists a positive constant $\xi_{1}>0$ such that the following relation holds:

$$
\left\|\delta_{t}\right\|_{\infty} \leq \xi_{1} \Longrightarrow \rho\left(\left\|\delta_{t}\right\|_{\infty}\right) \leq \frac{\epsilon}{2}
$$

Therefore, combining Eq. (37) and Eq. (38) and given that the conditions in Theorem 1 hold, for every $\epsilon>0$ there exists $t^{*} \in(-\infty, T]$ and $\xi_{1}>0$ such that if $\left\|\delta_{t}\right\|_{\infty} \leq \xi_{1}$ then

$$
\left\|\dot{\tilde{Z}}_{t}\right\|_{F} \leq \epsilon, t \in\left(-\infty, t^{*}\right]
$$

That is, for small disturbances $\delta_{t}, \dot{\tilde{Z}}_{t}$ will eventually enter and stay inside the ball of radius $\epsilon$.

$$
S^{*}=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
R^{11}+B^{1 \top} Z^{1 *} B^{1} & \ldots & B^{1 \top} Z^{1 *} B^{N} \\
B^{2 \top} Z^{2 *} B^{1} & \ldots & B^{2 \top} Z^{2 *} B^{N} \\

B^{N \top} Z^{N *} B^{1} & \ldots & R^{N N}+B^{\tilde{N} \top} Z^{N *} B^{N}
\end{array}\right]
$$

By Assumption 1, the unregularized $S_{t}$ in Eq. (11) and $S^{*}$ in Eq. (41) are of full rank. Therefore, $\inf _{t} \sigma_{\min }\left(S_{t}\right)=v>0$. In addition, we observe that when $\sum_{i, j \in[N]} \lambda_{i, j} \rightarrow 0$, we have $\hat{S}_{t} \rightarrow S_{t}$ and $\hat{Z}_{t} \rightarrow Z_{t}$ pointwise in $t$. By the continuity of the singular values, this implies that for every $t^{*} \in(-\infty, T]$ there exists $\xi_{2}>0$ such that if $\sum_{i, j \in[N]} \lambda_{i, j} \leq \xi_{2}$ then $\sigma_{\min }\left(\hat{S}_{t}\right) \geq$ $v / 2^{4}$ for all $t \in\left[t^{*}, T\right]$. Given that $\left\|\dot{\tilde{Z}}_{t^{*}}\right\|_{F} \leq \epsilon$, we can subsequently prove that $\left\|\dot{\tilde{Z}}_{t}\right\|_{F} \leq \epsilon$ for all $t \in\left(-\infty, t^{*}\right]$ by induction. In particular, from Lemma 1, if we require

$$
\frac{\sum_{i, j \in[N]} \lambda_{i, j}}{\left(\frac{v}{2}\right)^{2}} \leq \xi_{1}
$$

then we guarantee (38) holds at time $t=t^{*}$, and thus $\left\|\dot{\tilde{Z}}_{t^{*}-1}\right\|_{F} \leq \epsilon$ from Eq. (37). (42) and Lemma 1. We can follow this argument recursively and show that $\left\|\dot{\tilde{Z}}_{t}\right\|_{F} \leq \epsilon$ for all $t \in\left(-\infty, t^{*}\right]$, and thus

$$
\limsup _{t \rightarrow-\infty}\left\|\dot{\tilde{Z}}_{t}\right\|_{F} \leq \epsilon

To conclude, recall that the above results hold if we choose $\xi$ in Corollary 1 to be $\xi=\min \left(\left(\frac{v}{2}\right)^{2} \xi_{1}, \xi_{2}\right)$.

At the terminal stage, the single-stage difference between the unregularized policy $P_{t}$ and regularized policy $\hat{P}_{t}$ is given by $-\sum_{i, j} \lambda_{i, j} M_{t}^{-1} \theta_{i, j}^{*}$. The matrix $M_{t}^{-1}$ is generally dense in our experiments. Therefore, although $\lambda_{1,1}$ is zero, the non-zero values of $\lambda_{2,1}$ and $\lambda_{3,1}$ mean that $-\sum_{i \in\{2,3\}} \lambda_{i, 1} M_{t}^{-1} \theta_{i, 1}^{*}$ may still introduce a small bias to block $(1,1)$ of the policy matrix $\hat{P}_{t}$. This effect can similarly occur at earlier stages of the game. One could potentially mitigate this minor bias in unregularized and decoupled blocks in the policy matrices through heuristic adjustments. However, since the impact of the accumulation is minimal in our experiments (up to only $0.35 \%$ ), we did not implement specific corrective measures.

abstract:
Feedback Nash equilibrium strategies in multi-agent dynamic games require
availability of all players' state information to compute control actions.
However, in real-world scenarios, sensing and communication limitations between
agents make full state feedback expensive or impractical, and such strategies
can become fragile when state information from other agents is inaccurate. To
this end, we propose a regularized dynamic programming approach for finding
sparse feedback policies that selectively depend on the states of a subset of
agents in dynamic games. The proposed approach solves convex adaptive group
Lasso problems to compute sparse policies approximating Nash equilibrium
solutions. We prove the regularized solutions' asymptotic convergence to a
neighborhood of Nash equilibrium policies in linear-quadratic (LQ) games.
Further, we extend the proposed approach to general non-LQ games via an
iterative algorithm. Simulation results in multi-robot interaction scenarios
show that the proposed approach effectively computes feedback policies with
varying sparsity levels. When agents have noisy observations of other agents'
states, simulation results indicate that the proposed regularized policies
consistently achieve lower costs than standard Nash equilibrium policies by up
to 77% for all interacting agents whose costs are coupled with other agents'
states.
